#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:3
msgid "The writing and reporting of assertions in tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:11
msgid "Asserting with the ``assert`` statement"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:13
msgid ""
"``pytest`` allows you to use the standard python ``assert`` for verifying "
"expectations and values in Python tests.  For example, you can write the "
"following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:17
msgid ""
"# content of test_assert1.py\n"
"def f():\n"
"    return 3\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    assert f() == 4"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:27
msgid ""
"to assert that your function returns a certain value. If this assertion "
"fails you will see the return value of the function call:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:30
msgid ""
"$ pytest test_assert1.py\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-6.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-1.x.y\n"
"cachedir: $PYTHON_PREFIX/.pytest_cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR\n"
"collected 1 item\n"
"\n"
"test_assert1.py F                                                    [100%]\n"
"\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"______________________________ test_function "
"_______________________________\n"
"\n"
"    def test_function():\n"
">       assert f() == 4\n"
"E       assert 3 == 4\n"
"E        +  where 3 = f()\n"
"\n"
"test_assert1.py:6: AssertionError\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"FAILED test_assert1.py::test_function - assert 3 == 4\n"
"============================ 1 failed in 0.12s ============================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:54
msgid ""
"``pytest`` has support for showing the values of the most common "
"subexpressions including calls, attributes, comparisons, and binary and "
"unary operators. (See :ref:`tbreportdemo`).  This allows you to use the "
"idiomatic python constructs without boilerplate code while not losing "
"introspection information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:60
msgid "However, if you specify a message with the assertion like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:62
msgid "assert a % 2 == 0, \"value was odd, should be even\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:66
msgid ""
"then no assertion introspection takes places at all and the message will be "
"simply shown in the traceback."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:69
msgid ""
"See :ref:`assert-details` for more information on assertion introspection."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:74
msgid "Assertions about expected exceptions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:76
msgid ""
"In order to write assertions about raised exceptions, you can use :func:"
"`pytest.raises` as a context manager like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:79
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_zero_division():\n"
"    with pytest.raises(ZeroDivisionError):\n"
"        1 / 0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:88
msgid ""
"and if you need to have access to the actual exception info you may use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:90
msgid ""
"def test_recursion_depth():\n"
"    with pytest.raises(RuntimeError) as excinfo:\n"
"\n"
"        def f():\n"
"            f()\n"
"\n"
"        f()\n"
"    assert \"maximum recursion\" in str(excinfo.value)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:101
msgid ""
"``excinfo`` is an ``ExceptionInfo`` instance, which is a wrapper around the "
"actual exception raised.  The main attributes of interest are ``.type``, ``."
"value`` and ``.traceback``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:105
msgid ""
"You can pass a ``match`` keyword parameter to the context-manager to test "
"that a regular expression matches on the string representation of an "
"exception (similar to the ``TestCase.assertRaisesRegexp`` method from "
"``unittest``):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:109
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def myfunc():\n"
"    raise ValueError(\"Exception 123 raised\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_match():\n"
"    with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=r\".* 123 .*\"):\n"
"        myfunc()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:122
msgid ""
"The regexp parameter of the ``match`` method is matched with the ``re."
"search`` function, so in the above example ``match='123'`` would have worked "
"as well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:126
msgid ""
"There's an alternate form of the :func:`pytest.raises` function where you "
"pass a function that will be executed with the given ``*args`` and "
"``**kwargs`` and assert that the given exception is raised:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:130
msgid "pytest.raises(ExpectedException, func, *args, **kwargs)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:134
msgid ""
"The reporter will provide you with helpful output in case of failures such "
"as *no exception* or *wrong exception*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:137
msgid ""
"Note that it is also possible to specify a \"raises\" argument to ``pytest."
"mark.xfail``, which checks that the test is failing in a more specific way "
"than just having any exception raised:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:141
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.xfail(raises=IndexError)\n"
"def test_f():\n"
"    f()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:147
msgid ""
"Using :func:`pytest.raises` is likely to be better for cases where you are "
"testing exceptions your own code is deliberately raising, whereas using "
"``@pytest.mark.xfail`` with a check function is probably better for "
"something like documenting unfixed bugs (where the test describes what "
"\"should\" happen) or bugs in dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:157
msgid "Assertions about expected warnings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:161
msgid ""
"You can check that code raises a particular warning using :ref:`pytest.warns "
"<warns>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:168
msgid "Making use of context-sensitive comparisons"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:172
msgid ""
"``pytest`` has rich support for providing context-sensitive information when "
"it encounters comparisons.  For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:175
msgid ""
"# content of test_assert2.py\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_set_comparison():\n"
"    set1 = set(\"1308\")\n"
"    set2 = set(\"8035\")\n"
"    assert set1 == set2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:185
msgid "if you run this module:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:187
msgid ""
"$ pytest test_assert2.py\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-6.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-1.x.y\n"
"cachedir: $PYTHON_PREFIX/.pytest_cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR\n"
"collected 1 item\n"
"\n"
"test_assert2.py F                                                    [100%]\n"
"\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"___________________________ test_set_comparison "
"____________________________\n"
"\n"
"    def test_set_comparison():\n"
"        set1 = set(\"1308\")\n"
"        set2 = set(\"8035\")\n"
">       assert set1 == set2\n"
"E       AssertionError: assert {'0', '1', '3', '8'} == {'0', '3', '5', '8'}\n"
"E         Extra items in the left set:\n"
"E         '1'\n"
"E         Extra items in the right set:\n"
"E         '5'\n"
"E         Use -v to get the full diff\n"
"\n"
"test_assert2.py:6: AssertionError\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"FAILED test_assert2.py::test_set_comparison - AssertionError: assert "
"{'0'...\n"
"============================ 1 failed in 0.12s ============================="
msgstr ""

